text:
Poco aroma a caramelo con un toque a col.
Aspecto correcto, pero poca retencion de espuma.
En boca caramelo y almibar, demasiado empalagosa

Tap at RnH East. Clear chestnut brown color, small off-white head. Aroma is sweetish raisiny, berryish, malty. Medium-bodied. Odd sweet bock with lots of raisins, sweet maltyness, light toasty notes. Quite far from German bocks. Ok but seems to overrated.
Backlog, ocena przepisana z untappd, w ramach uzupełniania profilu na ratebeer.
Süßlich malziger Antrunk mit milder passender Herbe. Spritzig, Noten von Schokolade, vollmundig. Spritzig, steigend schokoladig, weich. Langer Nachhall, Noten von Holz. Gut. 10/12/12/12/10/12
Pour a mahogany color with a large creamy canvas colored head. Notes of apples, brown sugar, smoke, and licorice. Little bit on the sweet side for my taste.

This was poured into a pilsener glass.
The appearance was a mostly dark brown color with a foamy rocky off white head that hangs around for a good minute and a half.
The smell takes on a ton of dark fruit, clingy to roasty to sweet bready/yeasty content rolling on into a sticky malt character.
The taste was moderately smooth and sweet with the sticky malt character bleeding nicely on into the entire flavor.
On the palate, this one sat about a medium in body with a fair sessionable to smooth sipping quality about it. Carbonation feels fairly light.
Overall, as a doppelbock, it definitely works, really nice!

Où, Quand, Comment : 

Dégustée en fût au Farmhouse Tap & Grill (Burlington, VT), le 5/9/2015.


Visuel :  
Couleur : cuivrée-orangée. 
Apparence : voilée. 


Arôme :  
Malt sucré, légèrement fruité (raisins), léger de pain grillé et de caramel, notes de noix. 


Goût :  
En entrée de bouche : Léger goût fruité (raisins, notes de petits fruits foncés) avec quelques notes épicées. 
Une dominante de malt sucré est présente avec un léger goût de caramel, des notes pain grillé et de houblon herbeux. 


En bouche :  

Corps : moyen.
Effervescence : moyenne.
Texture : légèrement huileuse.
Finale : moyenne, composée dun léger résiduel sucré avec des notes amères de rôti, dalcool et de houblon herbeux.

Got in a BIF from tasterschoice62. 500 ml bottle into tulip glass, no bottle dating. Pours slightly cloudy deep ruby red/brown color with a 1-2 finger dense and fluffy khaki head with good retention, that reduces to a thin cap that lingers. Light spotty soapy lacing clings on the glass, with a moderate amount of streaming carbonation retaining the cap. Aromas of big caramel, brown sugar, toffee, brown bread, toasted biscuit, nuttiness, chocolate, cocoa, light coffee, raisin, plum, fig, herbal, light pepper, and yeast/roasted earthiness. Very nice aromas with good balance and complexity of dark/roast/bready malt, dark fruit, and light-moderate earthy hop notes; with good strength. Taste of big caramel, brown sugar, toffee, brown bread, toasted biscuit, nuttiness, chocolate, cocoa, light coffee, raisin, plum, fig, herbal, light pepper, and yeast/toasted earthiness. Light-moderate herbal/spicy hop and roast bitterness on the finish; with lingering notes of caramel, brown sugar, toffee, brown bread, toasted biscuit, nuttiness, chocolate, cocoa, light coffee, raisin, plum, fig, herbal, light pepper, and yeast/roasted earthiness on the finish for a while. Damn nice complexity, robustness, and balance of dark/roast/bready malt, dark fruit, and light-moderate earthy hop flavors; with a great malt/bitterness balance and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Medium carbonation and medium-full body; with a very smooth, moderately creamy/bready, and fairly grainy/sticky/chalky balanced mouthfeel that is nice. Alcohol is very well hidden with only a light warmth lingering after the finish. Overall this is an excellent doppelbock style! All around great complexity, robustness, and balance of dark/roast/bready malt, dark fruit, and light-moderate earthy hop flavors; and very smooth and easy to sip on for the ABV. This has very prominent roasted flavors of a Schwarzbier along with with the dryness; but still has balanced doppelbock malty/fruity complexity as well. A very enjoyable hybrid of the two styles.

Bottle. Moderate to heavy malt aromas of roasted and cookie, light cooked orange for the hops, moderate dough for the yeast, with toffee and brown sugar in the background. Head is small, wispy, light beige, with spotty lacing and is mostly diminishing. Color is hazy reddish brown. Flavor starts moderately sweet and lightly acidic, then finishes moderately sweet and lightly bitter. Palate is on the fuller side of medium, creamy with a soft carbonation. Just like a Doppelbock is supposed to be. The right amount of sweetness with just the right amount of a savory side.
500ml bottle. Clear copper with a foamy beige head. Flavors are toasted cereals, smoked meat, brown sugar, dried fruits and alcohol. Full body, moderate to good carbonation, creamy texture.

Orange-brown, medium tan head. The aroma was ok, some sweet malts but a little bit of unfreshness. Full body, alcohol well hidden. Sweet but not overly so, malty, some raisin and caramel flavors, well balanced, overall an enjoyable drinking experience.

Bomber poured into an odd tall, slim tulip style glass that promotes lots of foam. Unusually strong dopplebock, but a pretty tasty one. It is quite smooth and has a lot of well blended flavor, leaning toward the raisiny. Sweet and medium bodied, heavily malted with no reason to mention the noble hop, this is a good example of the more potent end of this traditional style.

Bottle. Pours dark amber with yellow thick head. Aroma is sweet, toffee, caramel, chocolate, hay, raisin, almonds. Taste is sweet, coffee, caramel, toffee, apricot. ABV is well hidden and well balanced beer.

Colour: bronze, ruby red. Very nice caramelly, fruity aroma. Sweetness, honey, caramel at first. Caramel dominates. Some fruits and honey in the aftertaste. 
Medium-bodied, medium carbonated, oily, quite nicely balanced interesting beer.
dark amber liquid with yellowish head. aroma of caramel, bread, silo, toffee, almond. taste of caramel and silo, heavy sweet, light bitter, light sour. full body, creamy, soft carb.
Bottle for patriot MNF in tense game. Cloudy dark brown beer. Nose is dark fruits, brown sugar, bready. Tastes of molasses, brown sugar, plum, granola, wheat bread. Hint of booze. Semi sweet.

Bottle @ home. Amber to ruby colour with a small off-white head. Smells sweet, raisins, malts, slightly toasty. Tastes raisins, sweet, malts, something slightly weird but not bad. Medium body, nice carbo.

21st September 2015Craft Tottenham Court Road. Keg. Bright clear amber beer, tidy pale cream colour head. Palate is light and mildly crisp. Sweet caramel malts, some cream. Touch of paper. Light finish. A sweet malty beer but fine.

Shared by czar, thanks! Pours a clear copper with a small beige head that leaves good lacing. Nose is of caramel, husky cereals and light alcohol. Taste is moderately sweet and carries on with the same caramel and cereals. Moderately bitter. Body is medium-full, carbonation moderate and mouthfeel sticky and syrupy. Pretty nice but not my style I guess...

Bottle 500ml. [Thx Czar]
Pours deep copper with low white head. Some lacing. Aroma is of fruits, raisins. Taste is of sugar, malt, bitterness, fruits, raisins. Palate: Full bodied. Soft carbonation. Overall: Good, malty.

pours unclear medium dark amber-orange with a small off-white cap, some retention and lacing. golden raisins - doughy and smooth maltiness, woodsy and spicy nuttiness, cherries, mint, hint of sweetness - brown sugar; medium dark roast coffee, lightly astringent leather and wood. light carbonation, medium body - oily; semi-sweet and woodsy-spicy finish. good doppelbock.

Keg at Craft Beer Co, Covent Garden, London. A dark mahogany/brown coloured pour with a medium off white head on top. Sweet, malty, caramel aroma. Tastes similar, sweet, malty, bready, caramel, slight roast. Very nice Doppelbock.
Botella. @Cimmeria, Oviedo 30/07/2015. Color caoba, espuma beige, aromas a malta, alcohol, sabor caramelo, cuerpo medio
From zombier. In Paulaner glass. Playing Memoria. Althought its not a style I like, i have to recognize that its good in its style because I find it drinkable

Draught @ taphouse w friends/ ancient DTU. Appearance: pours clear brown with good off-white creamy head and lacing. aroma/taste: caramel, raisins, nuts and dark fruits. palette: medium malty aroma, average carbonation, medium to full body, average to distinct sweetness, balanced by a medium bitterness, medium to long duration and an oily texture. Overall: very nice dark roasted dobbeltbock.

Cervesa molt bona, destaquen tan en gust com en aroma els tocs dolços de la malta.
Cerveza muy buena, destacan tanto en sabor como en aroma los toques dulces de la malta.

Brown pour from 16oz bottle from trade (Zach). White head, very thin. Sweet biscuit, malty aroma. Raisin, maple, brown sugar, a little alcohol flavor stands out too. Not bad at all, aquired taste for this style id imagine.

Tasting at MattsDark brown color, with generous compact beige head. The papery caramel aroma, woody, can be found very often in Germany too. The body is strong enough; semi-sweet caramel flavor, very shallow, leading to a short and boring final. Boozy final.Not enough malt quality. Too simple.
From tap. Pours hazy brown with a small white head. Aroma is breadish snd roasted malt. Bitter and dry breadish. Light metallic. Solid breadish and rather bitterness. Roasted and dry bitter finish.
Super smooth bock with nice sweetness and big malts, but balanced out by light dryness and making it very drinkable. Yum.
Bottle - Nice caramel and a touch of toast. Cloudy copper with a decent white head. Caramel, grains and a nice sweetness. Decent.

500mL bottle, pours a deep dark brown with a small beige head. Aroma brings out toasted malt, raisins, and toffee. Flavour is along the same lines, with toffee, toasted bready malt, and raisiny dark fruit. Chewy malty palate. Well-balanced and not too sweet. Very good.

Pours dark brown with a white head. Sweet malty aroma and taste, some caramel, nutty, brown sugar, sweet finish.
From tap at Taphouse. Dark brown colour with a small off-white head. Aroma and flavour of malt, caramel, bread and alcohol.

Draught at Taphouse.
Clear ruby colored with a medium sized off-white head.
Sweet and malty aroma of hay and caramel with notes of dried fruits.
Sweet and malty flavor of caramel, chocolate, hops and dried fruits.
Sweet finish.

Sweet malty aroma and taste, some caramel, nutty, brown sugar, sweet finish. Decent doppelbock.

---Sent via Beer Buddy for iPhone

500ml bottle. Clear brown colour with average, frothy, half-way lasting, minimally lacing, beige head. Nuttily malty, fruity aroma, hints of sultana, fig. Taste is nuttily malty, fruity, hints of sultana, fig, yellow stone fruit; soft palate creamy texture.
On tap at Biercab. Brown colour with tan head. Malt, dried fruits, toffee, bread aroma. Sweet, malt, caramel, dried fruits, bread, toffee, raisins taste. Medium body.

Deep brown pour with a thin white head. The nose has a great rich
cooked malt aroma. Toasted grain and a bit of soft malt sweetness.
Rich, sweet and delicious. Theres a lot of toffee, treacle, cooked
malt and a bit of plum and sweet toasted grain. Sweet and chewy. Clean
and clear. The malts really show through. Delicious brew.

My Bottom Line:
This Doppelbocks bready lengths, surrounded by comfortable Munich malt, dwell in a refined and highly authentic presentation.

Further Personal Perceptions:
-A sheet of foam covers the gleaming copper-hued mahogany.
-Alcohol is a no show in the flavor profile.
-Drinkability is higher than most of this style. Residual sugar levels are low, as you can imagine.
-Munich malt and their accompanying residual sugars also create dark cherry connotations.

Bottle.
Clear chestnut brown. Big vanilla and caramel aroma, I thought my wife lit sons kind of candle.. Wafting. Very clean tasting, caramel, fig, medium bitterness, delicious.

Draft at Eulogy. Dark clear copper brown pour with a slim white ring. Full body. Has the general character of a doppelbock. Black cherry cordials. Chocolate pudding. Vanilla toffee caramels. Plums. Fresh figs. Bettered expectations.

Bottle. Deep red with light beighe head. In aroma raisins, malt, caramel and tofee. In taste very smooth, caramel, raisins, sweet maltiness. The beer was full bodied, soft carbonation, medium bitter finish. Very good doppelbock.

Bottle. This pours clear dark ruby with a a small creamy beige head. Strong chocolate malty character with nutty notes. Rye crackers. Huge malty flavor. Chocolate notes. Nuts, ripe black berries and has a deep roasted nutty finish. I love it!

Cerveza tomada en el Kraken Oviedo.


Bastante alcoholica. Color rojizo turbio.
Sabores afrutados y ajerezados.

Apenas hace espuma.

Potente.

Medium beige head. Clear deep red body with ongoing carbonation.
Raisiny perfumy syrupy aroma, very delicate, with spicy toffee notes.
Dry-sweet spicy raisiny toffee taste with wooden herbal notes.
Wonderfully delicate. Wow. Full-bodied. Mild, soft, smooth
mouthfeel. Dryish raisiny chocolatey dusty caramel aftertaste with
rye crisp bread, nutty, teak wood notes. Lovely, lovely
flavours, melding together just right. Im really impressed. Didnt
have high hopes for this one, but wow. (0.5l bottle, from Fish & Beer,
Copenhagen. Its been in the cellar roughly 9 months.)

Attractive amber pour with tan foam. Caramel chews and bread dough but theres a bit of a stale quality. Maybe got trapped at the back of the fridge too long? Based on the other reviews, will have to give it another shot.
4 oz pour on draft at Jacks Abby. Dark amber/brown with beige head. Aromas of dark fruit, caramel, citrus. Tastes of dark fruit, caramel, toffee. Medium body with a dry finish.

Pours dark reddish amber, med tan head. Aroma is sweet malt, raisin, brown sugar, caramel, nutty, prune. Flavor is sweet pruney malt, doughy french toast malt, berry, light spicy hop. Medium body, some sticky boozy malt. Very well balanced nice stuff.

Pours a copper from a bottle, aroma is of caramelly golden raisins, like some European pudding or something. Flavor adds some roasted nuts, good bitterness to counterbalance the sweet malt. Rather big mouthfeel with some good alcohol burn at the end. Good beer.
Gedronken bij mijn neef benzai op zijn verjaardag. Robijnrood. Karamelsmaak en geur. Lichte tinteling in de nasmaak.

Bottle @ my birthday shared with my dad and Inoven. Lightly hazy dark ruby red color, medium sized beige head. Aroma is malts, caramel, nuts, lightly earthy. Taste malts, caramel, nuts, lightly sweet, lightly earthy, a hint of chocolate. Decent body and carbonation. Not bad at all.

Pour from a bottle left over from my trip to the brewery earlier this year. Dark copper amber-ish pour with a think white head. Big malty nose. Caramel, chewy malty goodness. Nice boozy heat in the finish, not too much - just right!
Pours a dark amber color with an off white head leaving little lacing. Mild aroma with barely noticeable malt note. Light flavor with malt notes. Unimpressive beer overall.
Bottle. Reddish pour, white head. Aroma is fruity and malty. Taste is malty. Dark fruits. Raisin and plum. Malty back end. Overall decent.

Beautiful mahogany hue topped by a long lasting beige head. Rich caramel and toffee notes with dark bread characteristics. Slight twangy crabapple and fig notes for some complexity. Very faint herbal hop tone upon the finish. Solid brew but just short of the best of the genre.

Botella de 50 cl en el momento en cimmeria el 12-09-2014. color ámbar oscuro cerezo. Aromas y sabores maltosos con toques de caramelo tostado. Cuerpo medio de 9 vol fácil de beber. Dopplebock especiada y dulce sin muchas sorpresas.

Single bottle from DeBucas. Poured into a snifter. A deep ruby brown color with a thick tan head that quickly fades to nothing. Low carbonation. Aroma of sweet earthy prunes with booze. Flavor is smooth and malty with booze. Somewhat warming. Goes down smoothly. First glass was much better than the first though.

A clear brown colored beer, with a firm beige head. It has a little aroma, some fruits with a litte yeast. The taste starts sweet, it become stronger fruity. Than moving to some bitter. The aftertaste has sweets from alcohol with bitter notes and hints of fruits.

Bottle. Pretty reddish-brown color with a tall head. Nose of chocolate fudge, raisin, dried plums. Rich malt flavors, fudge, raisins, some port. Tangy fruit and soft bitterness in the finish. Full and silky, but not heavy. Lovely high-alcohol doppelbock.

Ins Glas ergießt sich ein rötlichbraunes Bier mit ordentlicher beigen Schaumkrone. Geruch röstmalzig, Karamell, etwas Schoklade, sehr vollmundig. Geschmack süß nach Karamell und Schokolade, etwas Röstmalzig, den Alkohol spürt man auch deutlich.

Bottle bought @ bierkompass.de Pours hazy reddish brown with a rather thin fizzy mocha head that doesnt leave and trace on the glass while dissipating. Smell is malty and slightly floral with sweet dark bread, caramel, butterscotch, dried flowers, moist soil, cocoa powder, hay and orange zest. Taste is slightly sweet, slightly bitter, malty and floral with sweet dark bread, caramel, buttered biscuits, chocolate covered graham crackers, prunes, hay, moist soil and orange zest. Mouthfeel is soft, round, slightly boozy and medium to full bodied. Finish is slightly sweet, slightly bitter, malty and floral with sweet dark bread, chocolate covered graham crackers, prunes, raisins, hay, alcohol and orange zest. Pretty strange but I like it

Bottle 500ml. @ home on the terrace. [ As Jacks Abby Saxonator Dunkles Doppelbock ].Clear medium to dark brown amber color with a average, frothy, good lacing, mostly lasting, off-white head. Aroma is moderate malty, caramel, dark malt, dark berry, sweet malt. Flavour is moderate to heavy sweet and light moderate bitter with a long duration, sweet malt, sugary, caramel, dark fruit. Quit bock alike. Body is medium, texture is oily to watery, carbonation is soft. [20140629]
Very chocolate brown colour. A tad above average mouthfeel. Malty, tingly carbonation. Decent drinkability.

50 cl bottle @ Timo A.
Pours clear copper color with a small head. Grainy and slightly malty aroma, some roast and caramel notes. Nice creamy palate, bready and malty flavor, some toasty notes, caramel, faint nut notes and wood. A positive surprise.
4324

500 ml bottle. Pours a dark ruby amber colour with a white head. Aroma is rather grainy with toasted whole-grain bread, mild herbal notes and some sweetness. Rich flavour of toasted bread, grains, pungent sweetness, herbs and mild red berries. Almost full bodied. Really rich and pleasant.
Bottled. A brown beer with a huge tan head. The aroma has notes of caramel, bread, and malt. The flavor is sweetbwith notes of caramel, alcohol, malt, and bread, leading yo a dry lcoholic finish.
Poured light reddish brown with a small off white ring. Aroma of sweet berries and nuts. Medium body, flavour as the aroma, liquorice, roast malt.

Barwa: głęboko miedziana, klarowna. Piana w kolorze ecru, drobno pęcherzykowa, średniej wielkości, względnie szybko opadająca, ale ładnie oblepiająca szkło.

Aromat: słodowy, głównie chlebowy, karmelowy, toffi, czekoladowy, melanoidynowy, z dodatkiem suszonych owoców. Mimo dużej mocy alkohol całkiem dobrze ukryty. Całość w miarę ogrzewania coraz bardziej przyjemna i niemęcząca. 

Smak: słodowy, pełny, słodko - wytrawny, z pewnością nie jest to ulepek. Karmel, czekolada, spieczone ciasto, lekkie nuty owocowe oraz wyraźnie alkoholowy finisz. Tu również w miarę ogrzania się piwa smak czekoladowo - karmelowy wzmaga się. 

Piwo zakupione w Żywcu (kolejne :) ) z powodu rekomendacji na ratebeer. Oprócz tego zdobyło brązowy medal podczas tegorocznej edycji konkursu World Beer Cup w kategorii German Style Doppelbock. Powyższe zobowiązuje. Saxonator faktycznie przywraca (choć tylko częściowo) wiarę w bocki i powoduje, że zaczynam przypominać sobie za co je wcześniej ceniłem. Jest to konkretne i złożone, bezkompromisowe piwo, a mimo wszystko w stylu. Wprawdzie nie dorównuje innemu amerykańskiemu przedstawicielowi tego gatunku Perkulator Coffee Dopplebock z browaru Dark Horse, który chyba zostanie już na zawsze moim idealnym koźlakiem,ale i tak jest bardzo dobrze. Szkoda dość wysokiej ceny, ale piwa z USA niestety muszą przebyć dość długą drogę do Polski i częściowo można to zrozumieć.

Pours a clear amber color with just a small whips of a head. Aromas of caramel, toffee, biscuit. Taste is semi sweet with low bitterness. Flavors of dark brown sugar, caramel, sweet dough, unsalted pretzels. Finishes very sweet, borderline cloying. I really love most of jacks abby offering but ths one just misses the mark. Wouldnt drink again.

UPDATED: AUG 28, 2014 500ml bottle @Cimmeria,Oviedo. 30-06-2014.
BBD: not found.
In short: a sweet and roasty dark lager.
Pours quite clear dark amber-copper, with nice off white head, poor lacing. Roasty, liquorice, ripe fruit aromas. Medium body, average carbonation, some oily texture. Taste is caramel, roasty, liquorice, ripe fruit. Smooth and enjoyable, but not a classic doppelbock example.
Bottle, rudy brown pour, aroma is toasty, taste was very grassy and a fair bit bitter, it was a pretty interesting offering

Bottle from Voldby. Clear dark brown with an off-white head. Aroma is sweet, malty, caramel, nutty and dried fruit. Flavor is quite sweet and moderate bitter. Dry and moderate bitter finish with a little alcohol. 250614

Bottle,9%. Clear dark brown with small off-white head. Aroma is malt, caramel, toasted, chocolate and nuts. Flavour is malt, caramel, chocolate, nut, medium sweet, little toasted, hop and a little bitter.

Bottle at home. Medium high fluffy off-white lasting head. Clear ruby body. Relatively sweet roasted malt caramel dried fruit cocoa aroma. Mild and relatively sweet roasted malt caramel cocoa flavor without much hops bitterness, low carbonation and a long sweet finish. Would never have guessed the alcohol percentage.

Cant say I am impressed. Mostly light roasted maltiness, some caramel, some dried fruits, bit bready. I expect more intense aroma from doppelbock. Mostly sweet with light bitterness in finish. Quite well balanced, but feels bit too thin for me

Very respectable double bock. Malty sweet, toasted, nutty on nose, thick bodied - as it should be. Beige-yellowish rocky top. Very interesting visual texture - like bubbly and silky at the same time, amber-reddish, intense color. Some notes of wood in aroma. A bit boozy on nose at the start but not later, light warming in palate, thick-oily texture, soft carbonation;
Caramely, sweet and light darker malts bitter taste. This brew is not complex one but very enjoyable.

Beauty! Pours brown with a quickly fading head and no lacing. Nose is fig and syrup. Notes of figs, dark fruit like plums, pancake syrup, some nuts and a bit of roasted grain. Taste medium/heavy sweet and light bitterness. Body somewhat creamy with medium carbonation. Very drinkable alc well hidden.

I poured a 500ml bottle into a tulip glass. There was no freshness date and it cost $5.49 ($0.32 per ounce).

Appearance: Beautiful strawberry-red hue; translucent with no visible carbonation. Pours to a large, tan, foamy head which dissipates and leaves no lacing on the glass.

Smell: Strong cherry and other dark fruits; minor alcohol presence.

Taste: Jacks Abby is a new brewery whose niche is lagers. Whether the beers are traditional lager styles is a bit of a mystery. Though their beers do make a good case against the reliance on traditional styles with Saxonator Dunkles Dopplebock being a good example of what I mean. Theres definitely a lot of character to this beer that makes is reminiscent of some of the great German examples, though its still unique enough to blur style guidelines. Thats okay with me since the end result is a tasty beer.

The palate is an interesting hybrid of flavors found in styles of doppelbock, barleywine and American Strong Ale. Much like the aroma, dark cherry, raisin and fig are all quite prominent. I detect a hint of toffee or caramel, though its more of an afterthought. Mild bitterness on the finish with some faint chocolate flavor and a distinct alcohol presence as well. All the flavors here are quite pleasing, though Ive experienced similar palates that were even more robust. If this beer were rich and cloying it wouldnt be a flaw.

Drinkability: Jacks Abby Saxonator is one of those beers where its ABV works for it and against it simultaneously. For it in that the 9% ABV is well masked in the palate and the weight. Against it in that it doesnt seem to be completely efficient as it has the flavorfulness of something closer to 6%. However, the delivery process is nice with a calm, soft mouthfeel and smooth finish and a clean mouthfeel (a little too clean, actually).
Bottle. Pours an amber color with a small off-white head. Has a sweetish malty grainy spicy caramel aroma. Sweetish malty caramel and dark fruit flavor. Has a sweetish malty caramel finish.
Nezinu vai nav mans stils, bet diegan piezemēts un grūti ko labu uzrakstīt, alus kā tāds ir labs, kas ieplūst decent alus kategorijā un vieneriz pērkams ķesīa pēc.
UPDATED: MAY 29, 2014 Bottle. Pours dark reddish brown with cream off white head. Nose/taste of raisin, dark fruit, roasted nuts, maple, caramel, nutella toast and honey. Medium/full body.
Bottle. Creamy off-white good mostly lasting head. Red amber colour. Moderate malty and light hoppy aroma. Moderate bitter flavor. Average moderate bitter caramellic finish. Creamy palate.
Bottle from Voldby. Nice head with good duration. Color is brown. Aroma and taste are candy sugar, rich caramel, fruits, nuts, malt and hops. Nice and sweet.

500 ml bottle purchased at One Stop Market. Dark rusty brown color with thin lasting retention. Aroma is a solid amount of raisins, plum and notes of fresh baked, dark bread. Really nice. 
Rich malt flavors of caramel soaked raisins, fruit cake, some winter type spices, leading into a earthy, nutty malt bite toward the back of the sip. Malts are layered in depth. Fuller in body with the alcohol barely noticeable after the rich sweetness. I really enjoy this brewerys fine craftsmanship, another tasty offering!

Tap. Pours a clear but dark brown with minimal head. Malty aroma. Nice flavor with some mild spice and raisin/currant aftertaste. Mild carbonation. I didnt especially notice the alcohol and thought it was well masked. Very good overall.

Color caoba, limpio y elegante, con una capa de de espuma color marfil muy ligera que desparece rápido. Aroma dulce, azúcar moreno y frutas confitadas, toques tostados. Cuerpo denso, maltoso, sabor dulce y afrutado con toques tostados y un ligero toque de alcohol al final. Muy rica.
Subtle notes of dark fruits and chocolate along with rich malt character. Smooth mouth feel with soft carbonation. Solid offering as per usual from Jacks.

Malt-forward aroma with a hefty alcohol base reminiscent of almond liquor. Well extracted, fairly complex malt profile with neutral yeast character, not even a sulphur note. Were playing with nut tonalities, multi-cereal toasted bread, rye-like, and a certain concentration of vanilla infused darkish fruits like raisins, all fairly focused and sticking together on the palate, yet leaving your tongue swiftly as alcohol dominates the finish and after-thoughts. Plenty of residual sugars or perhaps not so much, but the generous alcohol adds a sugary dash of its own. Fortunately, the tight small bubbles clean that up some and so do the polite, yet relatively efficient leafy, spicy background hops, hitting with a subtle bitterness just in time. I got a feeling Id have dug this more at 2% lighter, but it is generous malt extraction and thoroughly clean and pleasant.
Bottle at Mikkeller&Friends - thanks to Fredrik. Clear brown - white head. Nutty. Toasted. Sweetness. Ryebread. Too sweet.

500ml bottle pours semi clear dark reddish brown with 2 finger head. Nose is earthy dark bread, nuts, raisin, cereal. Taste is dark bready fruit, raisin, cracker, cereal, wheat. Finish is mildly bitter rustic dark grains, wheat bread, dried fruits. Nice stuff.

20-APR-2014, bottle @Henrik.
Clear mahogany with a creamy off-white head.
Aroma is fruit, bread, and bitterness. Taste the same. Bock on turbo but high ABV is well hidden. OK drink.

bottle pour..dark copper color light brown..aroma of figs..fig jam..caramel..that smell when you are near a nutshop down the shore..medium bodied with a very nice mouthfeel that oozes raisins, dates, wood and smoke characteristics..smooth..full of flavor..great example of the style.well worth seeking out...hides the 9% well..terrific offering..

Bottle. Pours deep amber with a beige head and lace. Aroma of caramel malts, a little dark fruit and roasted notes, and some floral hops. Flavor the same with a nice blend of the malts. Average to smooth texture. Decent for the style.

Bottle. Thanks bigbro. Pours deep clear red with a small, staying, creamy white head. Aroma has caramel, sweet malts, milky chocolate, red berries. Medium carbonation, fine dry and creamy mouthfeel. Flavour has caramel, red berries, sweet malts, doughy. Quite elegant with some bitterness and light alcohol warmth.

Bottled. Pours amber with an average tan head. Aroma of slightly roasted malt, caramel, raisin notes of prune. Sweet flavor that ends up more dry an with bitter noted. Medium bodied oily texture and soft carb. An excellent Bock.
Pours a clear amber with some cloudy, white ehad. Nose is malty, apples, caramel. Flavor is malty, sweet, caramel, coconut.
draft at Blue Monk, fuller bodied amber with purplish hues. Raisins & dark fruit heavy, touch of roastiness and wisps of smoke. Fuller flavored & bodied. Smooth flavor & mouthfeel. Well done
Aroma has toffee, caramel, coffee, fruit, and a little skunk that breathed off after a while. Flavor has caramel, molasses, and fruit, with some spice and drying alcohol in the finish.

Pours a beautiful toasty copper brown with perfect clarity and a faint ruby blush. Fat head of tan foam that fell quickly to a thin ring. Not much lace. Nose very tempting. Theres bread, sweet chocolate,caramel, dark fruits and a touch fo brown sugar. Taste is delightful with layered malt complexity on a medium body. Rich and rowdy malt shows itself off in a way thats frolicsome and fun. Caramel, bread, dark fruits, raisin, date and fig, a touch of brown sugar and a bit of soft faint chocolate and it even hints at nuts. It has laid a malt feast before you and then , like placing a single flower in a bud vase on a table, there is a touch of warmth from the alcohol to finish this crisp and dry. 

Simply excellent. The body is a bit thinner than some of the german dopplebocks but with impeccable balance and with flavors that captivate this beer is contemporary and stylish.

Beautiful, clear, dark reddish orange. Spotty lacing fitting of a boozy beer. Nose is big, featuring dark fruit and graham crackers. Its a very rich nose, more rolls off as it warms. Palate is very tingly, a bit warming, a bit of booze detected at the very back, but well hidden. Start lush and thick ends a bit drier. Taste is predominantly the dark fruit. This seems very much in character and execution with an authentic German Doppelbock. Prost!

Bottled 1/15/2014, drunk 3/11/14Beautifully clear deep garnet body with amber and dark honey highlights. Light beige head is initially large and recedes slowly to cover.Bright, ripe berry notes in the nose speak to the melanoidins and plenty of caramel and raisin lurks underneath. Rich, freshly baked brown bread and graham cracker notes further diversify the maltiness while just a touch of spicy hops and light alcohol dry the finish slightly. Just a touch of light hazelnut in there as well. Rich and complex and malty. All the good things a doppelbock should be...Acidic and fruity at first, lip smackingly delicious, with prunes, currants, blackberries and plum brandy notes all whirling about the palate. Lightly sweet caramel and hazelnut coffee notes with sweet cream and hints of licorice. Tons going on here and all very clean and elegant. Malty and rich, but without any syrupy sweetness or wortiness. Very full-bodied and strong, so youre not going to confuse it with even something like Salvator and certainly not Celebrator (a full 2.3% abv lower). Still, I didnt find myself feeling the alcohol and the attenuation and tight carbonation keep it on the drinkable side for its size. After warming and breathing, however, the alcohol does definitely make itself known.
Bottled - dark brown pour with large beige head, dark fruit, very malty and a bit roasty - slight bite on the taste, ok not amazing.

Bottle. Pours clear chestnut, with a medium tan head that dissipates fairly quickly with decent lacing. Aroma is caramel, roast, toffee, prune, spices. Flavor is spicy, medium sweet and light bitter, prunes. Medium body, fairly high carbonation, some acidity.  Kind of a metallic bitter finish that comes out over time.

Bottle. Pours beer bottle brown with a scant off white head. Aroma is cereal, raisins. Taste - this is a thick chewy beer with molasses, raisin, date and caramel flavors. There is a bit of grassy bitterness to balance all the sweet. Alcohol is fairly well hidden.
Bottle. Brown pour with tan head. Nutty malt aromas. Sweet and nutty flavors, hints of spice tones. Body is a little lighter than expected.
Pours a lovely clear amber brown with a small white head. Aroma is sweet and malty. Taste is sweet with hints of brown sugar and molasses. Reminds me of troegenator but a little better.
Bottle to glass. Dark Brown body with a thin white head. Nose is raisin and Fig. Taste is similar. Sweet, but not overly sweet. Smooth body as always.

Aroma is as the brewer describes: raisin, plum, fruitbread. Clear reddish tan. Dark, roasted husky sweetness. Really not hoppy, bitter insofar as it is strong. Heavy body you can chew over for a time. Right there with the my favorite bock from the old country, and none are particularly nuanced.

Aroma: Raisins, Plums, Sweet Bread

Appearance: Dark Amber Hue, Passes Some Light, White Head, Mild Lacing

Taste: Sweet Bread, Raisins, Dates

Mouthfeel: Average Carbonation, Medium Bodied, Lightly Sweet
Smooth at 9% and extremely well-made. Reminded me of the Andechs doppel in its mouthfeel. The normal JA hop profile is not there and good that its not. Malt rules here.

50cl bottle. Large beige head atop clear dark amber body. Aroma is moderately sweet, caramel, raisin, some prune, light roast. Taste is moderately sweet, caramel, raisin, some plum. Medium body, light stickiness, warming, alcohol well contained.

Pours a slightly chill hazed reddish brown color with a fluffy beige head that persists forever. Caramel, molasses, dark burnt sugars and dark dried fruits, its a malt heads wet dream. Very light aromas of earthy hop provides almost no balance. The flavor is malty and rich with all of the aforementioned aromas playing a part in the flavor. Heavy molasses with a hint of smoke dominates the flavor while the other tastes add character. Rich sweet and frigging smooth. Medium to thick body with a moderate level of carbonation and a sweet bubbly syrupy mouthfeel. Great Americanized version of a dopplebock.
Usually dont drink dopplebocks but picked up a growler at Jacks after tasting.  Pours a reddish amber with a tan/beige head.  Smooth and silky for 9% alcohol, nice beer

Toasted malts, a little roast, dark fruit, a touch of alcohol. Pours brown with an off white head, nice lace. Flavors of darker fruit, toast, soft roast, moderate sweetness cleans up in the finish with just a hint of alcohol. Very well balanced and put together. A style I do not normally enjoy, this was very solid.
Rich robust lightly fruity and nicely rich doppelbock.  Im not a fan of the style but this one is done right.  Great nutty, malty and robust flavors that finish smooth and the abv is hidden.
Wow this is fantastic, great nutty and malty smooth flavors, rich and creamy, dry finish, perfect

500ml bottle-shared by CanIHave4Beers-thanks! and nice to meet you and the family.  cascading lt tan-hazy amber.  A-soft med malt-some toast.  T-med malt-some toast, some fruit, spice/earthy hops.  Crisp.

Bottle via "the box" ala Lushawn (aka Edmund Edmunds) 
Pours a perfectly orange color with a big head and nice lacing on the glass.

The aroma is very clean, and really doesnt have a ton going on... some rye bread and some light caramel... just one very mild smelling brew, but whats there is nice. 

The flavor is rye bread, some light caramel and a nice bitterness. The roasty character is very light and this is far drier and cleaner than what Ive come to expect from a 9% dopplebock... lightly dusty with a very clean malt profile and not a touch of the bit alcohol character. 

Very fine.

Thanks for sharing CanIHave4Beers. The is medium brown with some copper colorings. Sweet malty nose with some roasted walnut notes. There is also some toast. The taste is very sweet with some caramel and walnut notes. There is also some wood. Subtle and clean.
Sampled at EBF.  Pours a clear amber with some cloudy, white ehad.  Nose is malty, apples, caramel.  Flavor is malty, sweet, caramel, coconut.  Medium bodied, sweet finish.  Overly simplistic.

I dont work today so drink I shall. $3.80 for the bottle from Learys. To snifter it pours a crimson toned light brown with a sudsy vanilla head. Aromas of Munich malt, autumn leaves, mint, tobacco, cucumber, European hops, and cabbage. Tastes of Munich malt, raisins (as described on the bottle), and booze, and ends with an interesting earthy bite; wasnt salty, it had "soil" and "herbs" written all over it. My first few sips I thought it was too pungent, but its actually quite nice. Glad I didnt drain-pour. Fun beer.

Another solid brew from Jacks Abby. This has a really earthy flavor - chocolate malt maybe - that gives the beer a deep flavor. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

500ml bottle in a stem glass.  Pours deep amber with a lacy, beige head.  Aroma of caramel malts, a little dark fruit and roasted notes, and some floral hops.  Flavor the same with a nice blend of the malts.  Average to smooth texture.  Not a bad beer for the style.

November 2012 batch, 500 ml bottle into a tulip glass. 

A - Pours a clear dark red body. Lots of khaki foam, thick edging, with minimal lacing.

S - Caramel, dates, sweet brown sugar and malty bread. A bit of spice and booze on the end.

T - Dark fruit and caramel, spices, toasted malts, brown sugar. Syrupy sweet, a touch of booze on the end.

M - Thick and creamy, medium bodied with nice carbonation.

O - A very solid doppelbock. Not quite at the level of an Ayinger, but quite solid.

500mL bottle from trade with radarsock.  Cheers, Ander!  Pours a hazy amber with an off-white head.  Nose is cocoa, chocolate, raisins, some honey, and some yeast.  Flavor follows: a nice blend of raisin, slight banana, some yeast, cocoa, and fruit.  Medium in body and lingering raisiny finish.

pint.9 into a glass.  First standout point, this is a nice, smooth easy drinker. Taste is raisiny, plum, dates, and chewy granola mixed all over.  Color is deep burnt amber roasted with indulgence.  Head rises fast after a solid striaght pour, but subsides to froth the glass in a glancing presence.  There is a ruby read color omitting from the brew as well.  Aged canteloupe appears as well in the aroma.  A dark aftertaste emerges from the full body of the flavor, but then those raisins mix in and all is good. Another fine lager from Jack Abby.
Tap.  In general, not my favorite beer style.  So take review with a bath of salts.   Notez  include the following:  earthy raisin bread dough. Dough sweet breads.  Fine.

Bottle @ home via trade with Ernesto987. Thanks again! Pours a hazy orangish brown appearance with a creamy, light brown head.  Grape, plum, a bit nutty, light bubblegum, toasted malty, light caramel aroma. Brown sugar, toffee, fairly nutty, caramel, somewhat chewy malty flavor that is smooth and actually well attenuated. The carbonation seems a bit higher than I would like and there is some booze on the finish but this is a solid doppelbock.

500mL thanks to nmann08. Thanks bro! Pours a clear, deep ruby red. Thick, beige foam with good formation and retention. Nose is brown sugar, maple, sweet cookie. Taste is maple, cookie, shortbread, yellow cake. Dense, sweeter, nicely on style. Very German in feel.

Bottled, no date found. Poured a deep amber color into a lager glass. About two fingers if beige head. A little cloudy. Nice lacing on the glass. Smell is earthy, malty, yeasty almost bread like. Not picking up any fruity aromas. Taste is smooth malty sweet with slight bitterness. The word silky comes to mind. Nutty, a little bready, definitely earthy, and yeast character. Some acidity, maybe a hint of raisin or date notes. Very clean on the palate, light to medium body. Carbonation is moderate. Very smooth, balanced, and drinkable even with the alcohol. Seems well hidden to me. Enjoyable.

500ml bottle. Pours medium amber with a light tan head. Very well made beer for the style. Alot of dark fruit flavors and sweet caramel malt. Very little alcohol taste though a slight burn in the aftertaste due to the higher ABV.

Bottle shared by a local BA.  Pours a clear dark amber, almost mahogany color with a small beige head.  The aroma had dark fruits, hints of nuts, some earthy notes and caramel malt.  The flavor was roasted caramel malt, raisins with other dark fruits before finishing with a mild earthy notes.  Smooth with medium plus body.  A nice surprise at a tasting with some notable big beers.

Pours amber tinged mahogany into a stem glass. Tan head with medium retention recedes to hug rim. Sweet roasted nuts and caramel aromas. Thick with earthy toasted nuts and chocolate upfront turning slightly hot in the lasting sweet toffee finish.

On tap at the tasting room - Framingham, MA. Complex, dense and ranging brown aroma. Caramels, toasted nuts, and a big twinge of umami. Flavors are similar. Its funny. I really like this and think its a fantastically integrated dunkel-style doppelbock, with a really rich browned malt character, but it has that slightly too-umami glutamate character to it that often fatigues my palate quickly. I would only need about 6 ounces of this to make me happy and itd be worth it, because its a really classy beer.
